recurring_themes: Bench management has repeatedly driven outcomes: across weeks multiple teams left 15+ and even 20+ point performances on the bench (examples repeatedly cited include Justin Herbert, Matthew Stafford, Mark Andrews, Rome Odunze, Justin Fields, Jaxson Dart, George Pickens).
D/ST and kicker variance frequently swing matchups (examples: Vikings D/ST 32.0 in Week 3, Texans D/ST 18.0 in Week 7, kickers Brandon Aubrey 22.0 in Week 2, Cairo Santos 19.0 in Week 4).

High QB variance: some QBs massively outperformed projections (Josh Allen 38.76 Week 1, Patrick Mahomes multiple weeks), while other QBs posted major busts (Caleb Williams Week 7, Justin Fields some weeks), making the QB slot a frequent source of matchup volatility.
Many matchups were decided by narrow margins where single bench/lineup choices would have flipped results (multiple documented games with margins under ~2 points).

upsets_and_blowouts.description: Gronk for my johnson produced the season's largest single-week blowout, scoring 173.14 to overwhelm Goff And Running (76.44) in Week 6; that game featured multiple multi-positional outliers for the winner (Bijan Robinson 32.8, Cam Skattebo 30.0, Dallas Goedert 21.5).
Several smaller upsets/overperformances: Puka Puka and D.J. Chark Week posted large offensive weeks (149.96 and 147.30 respectively) that flipped projected outcomes in Week 4.

close_games_and_frequency.observation: Multiple weeks included nail-biters decided by single-digit points; bench/inactive decisions and D/ST/kicker variance were frequent deciding factors.

scoring_variability.observation: Team weekly outputs have ranged from the low 60s up through the 170s. Many teams posted weeks well above projections driven by 2–4 simultaneous outliers (QB + RB/WR + D/ST/kicker).
notable_outlier_types: High RB/WR breakout games (e.g., Rico Dowdle 206 rushing yards Week 5; Jacory Croskey-Merritt 111 rush yards + 2 TDs Week 5).
D/ST and kicker spikes (multiple weeks with D/STs scoring double-digit points and kickers scoring 10+ points).

team_level_trends.scoring_pattern: Very high ceiling weeks (173.14 in Week 6); roster has produced multiple multi-player blowouts when several starters align.
key_player_impacts: Bijan Robinson, Cam Skattebo and Jaxon Smith-Njigba provided multi-week high-impact contests (big contributors in Week 6).
Dallas Goedert and others have produced large swing weeks (Goedert 21.5 Week 6).
team_level_trends.owner_behavior_observations: Occasional large bench upside (Justin Herbert, etc.) has been left unused in some weeks (e.g., Week 5/7 bench QB production noted).

team_level_trends.scoring_pattern: High-upside offense that can hit explosive WR/RB/QB weeks (Puka Nacua, Ja'Marr Chase, Dak Prescott, Rico Dowdle). Also shows volatility: very high weeks and some very low weeks (63.44 in Week 3).
key_player_impacts: Rico Dowdle produced two multi-week blowups (206 rushing yards Week 5; 31.9 points Week 6).
WR duo Ja'Marr Chase and A.J. Brown produced a 1–2 punch in Week 7 (30.1 and 26.1).
team_level_trends.owner_behavior_observations: Benches have contained major scoring at times (Kayshon Boutte, Kimani Vidal), and Puka occasionally left big bench scoring unused (e.g., large bench scores documented Week 6).

team_level_trends.scoring_pattern: Generally high team points across the season (consistent top-tier Points For by mid-season). Christian McCaffrey is the primary dependable engine; TE/WR weeks (Tyler Warren, Michael Pittman Jr.) and occasional kicker/defense outliers have helped.
key_player_impacts: Christian McCaffrey produced massive weeks (35.6 in Week 7) that often anchor wins.
Matthew Stafford produced multiple bench-high weeks (e.g., 27+ on bench) suggesting owner sometimes under-uses bench QB upside.
team_level_trends.owner_behavior_observations: Repeated instances of leaving a high-scoring QB (Matthew Stafford) on the bench across weeks; negative D/ST weeks (Steelers D/ST -4 Week 7) have also cost points.

team_level_trends.scoring_pattern: High Points For across season (one of the top PF totals through Week 6). Strong RB/TE weeks (Quinshon Judkins, Jake Ferguson, Josh Jacobs) but QB volatility (Justin Fields bust week-to-week) can depress outcomes.
key_player_impacts: Running backs and TE (Josh Jacobs, Quinshon Judkins, Jake Ferguson) repeatedly deliver large positive variance.
Justin Fields has been a swing factor — huge bench weeks and also low-output starts.
team_level_trends.owner_behavior_observations: Left multiple high-value bench players unused in several weeks (e.g., Justin Fields, Chris Olave in Week 7 bench 24.3).

team_level_trends.scoring_pattern: Generally above-average offense with occasional WR/RB surges (Amon-Ra St. Brown, De'Von Achane). Susceptible to big negative swings when key starters (George Kittle, Mike Evans) are inactive or zero out.
key_player_impacts: Amon-Ra St. Brown produced multiple explosive weeks early in the season (Week 2, Week 3).
De'Von Achane has provided breakout RB weeks (Week 6).
team_level_trends.owner_behavior_observations: Has had bench depth (Justin Herbert, Josh Downs) but has also suffered several late-week inactive issues reducing expected starter output.

key_player_impacts: Bo Nix had a breakout mega-week (39.96 in Week 7) that single-handedly swung results.
Trey McBride has had multiple TE outperformance weeks.
team_level_trends.owner_behavior_observations: Has repeatedly left high bench scoring unused (Browns D/ST, Kyle Monangai) but also capitalized on defensive starts (Broncos D/ST Week 6).

team_level_trends.scoring_pattern: Very capable of explosive weeks (Mahomes + George Pickens Week 4 and Week 6), but also vulnerable to RB and D/ST busts. Bench QBs (Jaxson Dart) and WRs have produced and been left inactive multiple times.
key_player_impacts: Patrick Mahomes has been a reliable high-floor, high-ceiling performer.
George Pickens produced multiple large WR weeks (29.4 in Week 4).
team_level_trends.owner_behavior_observations: Repeat pattern of leaving high bench scores unused (Jaxson Dart, Jordan Addison) that could have provided margin in close losses.

key_player_impacts: Quarterback spot (Drake Maye/Jared Goff) has had productive weeks; WRs like DK Metcalf and Rashee Rice can swing totals.
Run-game failures have been a recurring issue in losses.
team_level_trends.owner_behavior_observations: Has left valuable bench pieces (Travis Kelce, Rhamondre Stevenson) unused; poor availability/inactives (Rashee Rice listed Inactive some weeks) have affected lineups.

Emeka Egbuka produced breakout weeks (multiple weeks >20 points).
team_level_trends.owner_behavior_observations: Repeated high-scoring bench outputs (Daniel Jones, Wan'Dale Robinson) left unused; BYE weeks for Josh Allen limited upside in some matchups.

key_player_impacts: D'Andre Swift has had multiple large weekly performances (Week 6 24.5).
Deebo Samuel produced several strong weeks but also had notable zero/low weeks.

repeat_underperformers_or_busts.trend: Some WRs have been boom-or-bust across weeks — producing large spikes in some weeks and near-zero in others (Zay Flowers left on bench Week 3 with 24.6 but also had low outputs other weeks).

player_level_trends.role_of_bench_players_on_outcomes: Across weeks, repeated cases where bench players scored 15–30 points (e.g., Mark Andrews 24.1, Rome Odunze 28.3, Matthew Stafford 27.4, Jaxson Dart 28.42, Kayshon Boutte 23.8) but remained unused, directly affecting game results. This is the single most-cited manager decision factor in weekly recaps.

common_risky_behaviors.behavior: Leaving very high-scoring bench players unused
examples: Justin Fields 29.52 left on bench (Week 1/Week 5 examples)
common_risky_behaviors.impact: Frequent missed opportunity to flip close losses or increase win margins; cited across multiple matchups and weeks.

common_risky_behaviors.behavior: Not starting freshly high-projected QBs or starting lower-floor QBs in some weeks
examples: Leaving Justin Herbert (27.92 Week 1) on bench; leaving Jared Goff (33.96 Week 2) on bench.
Starting QBs who then massively underperformed (Caleb Williams Week 7).
common_risky_behaviors.impact: QB decisions have directly swung several matchups due to high QB variance.

common_risky_behaviors.behavior: Retaining inactive/IR players in expected starting roles without replacements
examples: Multiple teams listed inactives/IR (Tyreek Hill, Mike Evans, Brandon Aiyuk, Austin Ekeler) reducing expected output.
common_risky_behaviors.impact: Availability/inactive management reduced expected scoring floors in several teams.

notable_smart_or_high-upside_moves.behavior: Starting D/STs or kickers that greatly outperform projection in specific weeks
examples: Vikings D/ST 32.0 (Week 3), Patriots D/ST 20.0 (Week 7 for Clever Team), Texans D/ST 18.0 (Week 7)
Brandon Aubrey K 22.0 (Week 2) provided a decisive boost for I Know Exactly What I’m Doing.
notable_smart_or_high-upside_moves.impact: Effective D/ST/K starts have flipped matchups and provided margin where skill players underperformed.

notable_smart_or_high-upside_moves.behavior: Riding RB/TE breakout weeks when they occur
examples: Owners who started late-season RB breakout weeks (Rico Dowdle, Jacory Croskey-Merritt, Quinshon Judkins) often secured wins despite other positional noise.
notable_smart_or_high-upside_moves.impact: Recognizing and starting in-form RB/TEs yielded outsized returns.

playoff_projection_and_analysis.methodology_note: Playoff projection uses available win-loss records through Week 7. Where teams share identical records, available Points For totals from mid-season summaries were used as the next tie-breaker since a complete head-to-head table was not provided in the input.

Among 4-3 teams, No Punt Intended had one of the higher reported Points For values (690.68 in Week 6 summary).
Points For 669.46 (Week 6), placing them next among 4-3 teams.

Points For 605.98 (Week 6) — rounds out the projected six-team playoff field based on record then PF.

playoff_risks_and_notes: This projection is provisional. If head-to-head results (not fully enumerated in the provided data) favor a different ordering among 4-3 teams, seed positions could change.

Several teams just outside the projected top 6 (multiple 3-4 teams) have sizable single-week upside and could displace current seeds quickly if they hit multi-player outlier weeks (documented examples: D.J. Chark Week, Goff And Running, OHHHHHHH YEAHHHHH!!!!).

Owner bench management will be a crucial determinant for the final regular-season ladder; many narrow games across Weeks 1–7 indicate a volatile landscape where one or two lineup choices can change playoff composition.

final_observations_and_data_driven_takea: Bench/inactive management has been the single most frequently-cited determinant of weekly outcomes — teams repeatedly lost or nearly lost despite having 15–30 unused bench points.
D/STs and kickers have produced outsized, often unexpected, week-winning contributions; owners who prioritized matchup D/ST/kicker starts were frequently rewarded.
QB volatility is high: owners who had the foresight to start high-upside QBs (or replace struggling QBs) in weeks with favorable matchups frequently gained decisive edges.
The playoff picture is tight: four teams sit at 4-3 and two at 5-2; with the documented scoring volatility it is likely the top six will continue to shuffle in the coming weeks.
